1473","1436":"1436","1456":"1456","25 September 1473":"25 september 1473","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","About 1420":"circa 1420","1418":"1418","1515":"1515","East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England":"East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England","Stretton, Staffordshire, England":"Stretton, Staffordshire, England","Glazeley, Shropshire, England":"Glazeley, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"About 1420–25 September 1473":"about 1420–25 September 1473","1418–1456":"1418–1456","1436–1515":"1436–1515","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1436":"1436","1456":"1456","25 September 1473":"25 September 1473","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","About 1420":"about 1420","1418":"1418","1515":"1515","East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England":"East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England","Stretton, Staffordshire, England":"Stretton, Staffordshire, England","Glazeley, Shropshire, England":"Glazeley, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ragon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   Ragan  .","In some cases possibly also French: from the oblique case of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Rago</i>, a short form of any of various names formed with the element <i>rag</i>, a short form of <i>ragin</i> ‘counsel’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ragan","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Regan  ."]}]},{"name":"E","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鄂, a short form of present-day Hubei province: (i) from E (鄂), the name of an ancient state (located in Henan province), destroyed by the king Zhou, last king of the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) from the placename E (鄂), the name of a fief (located in Shanxi province) in the state of Jin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the placename E (鄂), the name of a fief (located in Hubei province) granted to the royal members of the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) possibly a surname from minority ethnic groups in southwestern China. (v) said to be adopted as a new surname by Yue Ting, who changed his original name Yue (嶽) to E (鄂), because he fled to Huangmei in present-day Hubei province (called E (鄂) at that time) to avoid persecution after his father Yue Fei (1103–1142  AD ), a famous Chinese general in the Southern Song dynasty (1127 – 1279  AD ), was put to death by the then emperor."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady E Ragon Baroness Wylde was born about 1420, in East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir T W B Wylde Of Bromham. She died on 25 September 1473, in Glazeley, Shropshire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"About 1420–25 September 1473":"umbes 1420–25. september 1473","1418–1456":"1418–1456","1436–1515":"1436–1515","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1436":"1436","1456":"1456","25 September 1473":"25. september 1473","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","About 1420":"umbes 1420","1418":"1418","1515":"1515","East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England":"East Haddon, Northamptonshire, England","Stretton, Staffordshire, England":"Stretton, Staffordshire, England","Glazeley, Shropshire, England":"Glazeley, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"About 1420–25 September 1473":"noin 1420–25. syyskuuta 1473","1418–1456":"1418–1456","1436–1515":"1436–1515","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1436":"1436",